3:1 NADH:substrate up to 23%; reaction ceases above pH 10"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia adds to alpha-ketoglutarate to form a hemiaminal/iminium intermediate, which is reduced by hydride transfer from NADH to yield glutamate.", "reasoning": "This step is directly supported by recent experiments showing non-enzymatic reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate by NH3/NADH under mild prebiotic conditions with strong pH dependence (Rivas et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Thermal cyclization of glutamate to pyroglutamic acid", "inputs": ["mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "423-523K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "hydrothermal fluids; equilibrium reached rapidly near 523K; anoxic; dissolved H2 stabilizes glutamate/pyroglutamate pool"}, "mechanism": "Intramolecular dehydration cyclizes glutamate to the five-membered lactam pyroglutamate.", "reasoning": "Glutamate is known to cyclize readily to pyroglutamic acid under hydrothermal conditions; this is a major fate of glutamate at elevated temperature and a central part of its vent stability chemistry (Miller, 1953 reanalyses contextualized by Johnson et al., 2008; Menor-Salv\u00e1n et al., 2013; Ferreira et al., 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Hydrolytic reopening of pyroglutamic acid to glutamate", "inputs": ["mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "298-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "wet phases following heating; reversible reservoir behavior"}, "mechanism": "Lactam hydrolysis reopens the ring to regenerate glutamate.", "reasoning": "The literature review treats glutamate and pyroglutamate as a reversible pool; pyroglutamate is not merely degradation but a metastable reservoir that can preserve and later release glutamate equivalents (Ferreira et al., 2023; Shock et al. hydrothermal stability context summarized in the review)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Cyanosulfidic direct route", "description": "Surface cyanosulfidic homologation of HCN to 2-aminopentanedinitrile followed by hydrolysis to glutamate.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_006", "rxn_007"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Acrolein Strecker route", "description": "Volcanic/discharge acrolein feeds a Strecker-type conversion to the dinitrile precursor and then hydrolysis to glutamate.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_007"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_008", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Hydrothermal carbon fixation plus acrolein handoff", "description": "Hydrothermal acetate production seeds surface acrolein formation, which enters the Strecker route to glutamate.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_007"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_008", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Formate-fed surface cyanide route", "description": "Hydrothermal formate contributes reduced carbon to cyanide-rich surface chemistry that enters the cyanosulfidic glutamate precursor route.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_006", "rxn_007"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_003", "mol_006", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Iron-sulfur transamination route", "description": "Hydrothermal pyrrhotite-like thioester carboxylation yields alpha-ketoglutarate, which is transaminated by glycine to glutamate.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Biomimetic reductive amination route", "description": "Hydrothermal alpha-ketoglutarate is transferred into a mild biochemical pool for NADH-mediated reductive amination to glutamate.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_008", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name":